- My name's Ethel Jackson and
I wonder if you could just give

00:36:38.780 --> 00:36:42.650
us a quick update on where
things stand with the release

00:36:42.650 --> 00:36:47.300
of gene drive-edited mosquitoes?

00:36:47.300 --> 00:36:51.650
I know there's been a lot
of effort along those lines,

00:36:51.650 --> 00:36:54.350
and I'd just like to
know where that stands,

00:36:54.350 --> 00:36:57.720
in terms of
environmental release?

00:36:57.720 --> 00:37:01.421
- OK, so initially,
off-target effects on CRISPR--

00:37:01.421 --> 00:37:03.920
So CRISPR is, of course, being
looked at for a lot all sorts

00:37:03.920 --> 00:37:04.310
of things.

00:37:04.310 --> 00:37:05.780
Its biggest impact
is on research,

00:37:05.780 --> 00:37:07.446
just because it makes
everything that we

00:37:07.446 --> 00:37:09.035
do in the lab so much easier.

00:37:09.035 --> 00:37:10.910
But it's also being
looked at therapeutically

00:37:10.910 --> 00:37:11.990
for gene therapy and the like.

00:37:11.990 --> 00:37:14.198
And one obvious concern is
you want to program CRISPR

00:37:14.198 --> 00:37:16.280
to cut a particular
gene and no other genes,

00:37:16.280 --> 00:37:19.194
because if you accidentally cut
a tumor suppressor, that's bad.

00:37:19.194 --> 00:37:21.110
If you're doing gene
therapy on a lot of cells

00:37:21.110 --> 00:37:23.180
in a lot of patients,
you need to be sure

00:37:23.180 --> 00:37:25.134
that you're very, very accurate.

00:37:25.134 --> 00:37:26.550
So there's been a
lot of research,

00:37:26.550 --> 00:37:29.420
particularly in the
Boston area, by groups

00:37:29.420 --> 00:37:32.090
working to make CRISPR
even more specific.

00:37:32.090 --> 00:37:36.790
And the best versions now are--

00:37:36.790 --> 00:37:40.830
the off-target rate is
pretty close to undetectable.

00:37:40.830 --> 00:37:44.520
And that's great,
but just because you

00:37:44.520 --> 00:37:46.664
can't detect it doesn't
mean it doesn't exist.

00:37:46.664 --> 00:37:48.330
And so if you were
to roll out something

00:37:48.330 --> 00:37:52.330
to, say, 50 million
people and you're

00:37:52.330 --> 00:37:55.060
altering a billion
cells per person, which

00:37:55.060 --> 00:37:57.740
is a tiny fraction of the
cells in an individual's body,

00:37:57.740 --> 00:37:59.350
we can't test that many.

00:37:59.350 --> 00:38:04.730
So that's why CRISPR will be
great for medical problems

00:38:04.730 --> 00:38:09.140
where you're willing to take a
tiny risk of cancer in exchange

00:38:09.140 --> 00:38:11.570
for solving an actual problem.

00:38:11.570 --> 00:38:14.690
But it's not going to be useful
for but what one might call

00:38:14.690 --> 00:38:18.370
a 'recreational' gene therapy.

00:38:18.370 --> 00:38:23.980
Tick birth control-- the
preferred form of birth control

00:38:23.980 --> 00:38:24.640
is kill them.

00:38:27.850 --> 00:38:30.280
So we have lots of-- we
have lots of chemicals

00:38:30.280 --> 00:38:31.330
we use to kill ticks.

00:38:31.330 --> 00:38:34.510
And they're are concentrated,
of course, on deer.

00:38:34.510 --> 00:38:37.870
So there are these four poster
devices where you feed the deer

00:38:37.870 --> 00:38:42.300
and it basically rubs
pesticides on the deer

00:38:42.300 --> 00:38:44.010
to kill the ticks on them.

00:38:44.010 --> 00:38:45.600
There are also these
tubes where you

00:38:45.600 --> 00:38:47.850
have Permethrin-treated
cotton balls in the tubes.

00:38:47.850 --> 00:38:48.840
You leave them out.

00:38:48.840 --> 00:38:51.519
The local mice grab them and
use them for nesting material,

00:38:51.519 --> 00:38:53.310
and then burrow into
them in the Permethrin

00:38:53.310 --> 00:38:54.837
kills all the ticks on them.

00:38:54.837 --> 00:38:57.420
I'm not aware of anyone working
on actual tick contraceptives,

00:38:57.420 --> 00:39:00.720
however every couple of
months, I get an email

00:39:00.720 --> 00:39:02.940
from someone in
the world, usually

00:39:02.940 --> 00:39:06.250
from somewhere in the
United States, who says,

00:39:06.250 --> 00:39:08.040
why are you mucking
around with mice?

00:39:08.040 --> 00:39:10.590
Just use a suppression
gene drive.

00:39:10.590 --> 00:39:12.570
Standard version affects
the entire species

00:39:12.570 --> 00:39:16.237
to eliminate all the ticks.

00:39:16.237 --> 00:39:18.570
Which you might say, well,
how can a gene drive do that?

00:39:18.570 --> 00:39:20.278
Well, there's a couple
of different ways.

00:39:20.278 --> 00:39:22.114
The obvious one is
suppose the gene

00:39:22.114 --> 00:39:24.030
you're transmitting turns
them all into males?

00:39:26.910 --> 00:39:28.615
So I'm skeptical
that you can actually

00:39:28.615 --> 00:39:30.240
go all the way to
extinction, certainly

00:39:30.240 --> 00:39:31.620
not with a single
drive system, due

00:39:31.620 --> 00:39:33.270
to likelihood of
resistance, et cetera.

00:39:33.270 --> 00:39:36.060
But one could conceivably
do that except that the tick

00:39:36.060 --> 00:39:37.346
generation time is two years.

00:39:37.346 --> 00:39:38.970
So if you're willing
to wait a century,

00:39:38.970 --> 00:39:40.136
we might be able to do that.

00:39:43.560 --> 00:39:48.260
Let's see, next question was
vaccines and immunization

00:39:48.260 --> 00:39:49.730
history.

00:39:49.730 --> 00:39:52.890
And if we have--

00:39:52.890 --> 00:39:54.590
I don't really know on that one.

00:39:54.590 --> 00:39:56.652
I know that genetic
engineering in general,

00:39:56.652 --> 00:39:58.610
had we started with
something that was actually

00:39:58.610 --> 00:40:02.600
a problem that's obvious to
ordinary people as opposed to--

00:40:02.600 --> 00:40:06.420
or even played up that
recombinant insulin

00:40:06.420 --> 00:40:08.860
is recombinant.

00:40:08.860 --> 00:40:12.420
Everyone, raise your hand
if you take insulin--

00:40:12.420 --> 00:40:12.920
anyone?

00:40:15.560 --> 00:40:20.860
So that insulin, of course,
comes from engineered microbes.

00:40:20.860 --> 00:40:21.940
It's recombinant DNA.

00:40:21.940 --> 00:40:23.100
It's genetic engineering.

00:40:23.100 --> 00:40:24.510
It's GMO.

00:40:24.510 --> 00:40:26.460
But most people don't
think of it that way.

00:40:26.460 --> 00:40:28.350
We think about
genetic engineering

00:40:28.350 --> 00:40:30.810
in the context of Monsanto.

00:40:30.810 --> 00:40:32.550
And what do you
all those products

00:40:32.550 --> 00:40:35.870
do for the people who
buy them in the market?

00:40:35.870 --> 00:40:38.870
a couple of cents cheaper?

00:40:38.870 --> 00:40:40.620
That's just not enough.

00:40:40.620 --> 00:40:42.480
So that one I know
would be different.

00:40:42.480 --> 00:40:45.590
But vaccines, that
was a long time ago

00:40:45.590 --> 00:40:47.570
and it's hard to argue
with government control.

00:40:47.570 --> 00:40:51.350
And so I really don't know
the answer to that one.

00:40:51.350 --> 00:40:55.580
I think that the more we
invite people's voices,

00:40:55.580 --> 00:40:58.170
the better off we will be
because things will be safer

00:40:58.170 --> 00:41:01.070
and, I think, more acceptable to
people, if people have a voice.

00:41:01.070 --> 00:41:03.860
But beyond that, I
couldn't really say.

00:41:03.860 --> 00:41:06.410
And as for mosquito
gene drive systems,

00:41:06.410 --> 00:41:09.570
there are a number of
laboratories working on them.

00:41:09.570 --> 00:41:11.450
There may be some
that I don't know of.

00:41:11.450 --> 00:41:14.750
The current status is that
the things that you see

00:41:14.750 --> 00:41:19.100
that are published are not--

00:41:19.100 --> 00:41:23.770
most of the latest advances
have not been published.

00:41:23.770 --> 00:41:26.410
And most of the work,
in fact, everything

00:41:26.410 --> 00:41:30.280
other than our
collaborators and my lab--

00:41:30.280 --> 00:41:32.170
collaborators
particularly at Harvard

00:41:32.170 --> 00:41:35.020
and Flaminia Catteruccia
and George Church's group

00:41:35.020 --> 00:41:36.350
in particular.

00:41:36.350 --> 00:41:38.920
And we're working with Paul
Brindley at George Washington

00:41:38.920 --> 00:41:44.260
University on schistosomiasis
and with Pirbright University,

00:41:44.260 --> 00:41:50.790
Luke Alphey in the UK, and
University of Otago [INAUDIBLE]

00:41:50.790 --> 00:41:52.350
in New Zealand on rats.

00:41:52.350 --> 00:41:55.460
Those are the only projects
that are completely open.

00:41:55.460 --> 00:41:57.200
There's a bunch
of mosquito ones.

00:41:57.200 --> 00:41:59.930
Target Malaria has results
showing that-- where

00:41:59.930 --> 00:42:04.220
they have solved the problem
of the drive system acting

00:42:04.220 --> 00:42:06.840
after fertilization.

00:42:06.840 --> 00:42:10.141
And this is important if you're
doing the suppression drive

00:42:10.141 --> 00:42:12.390
that they're looking for to
reduce the population just

00:42:12.390 --> 00:42:15.780
because you need to ensure
that your offspring inherit

00:42:15.780 --> 00:42:18.300
one functional copy of a gene.

00:42:18.300 --> 00:42:19.930
That's important for fertility.

00:42:19.930 --> 00:42:22.530
So if you cut that copy
just after fertilization,

00:42:22.530 --> 00:42:23.710
it doesn't work.

00:42:23.710 --> 00:42:24.905
And that's been the huge--

00:42:24.905 --> 00:42:27.030
it also reduces the efficiency
of the drive system,

00:42:27.030 --> 00:42:29.580
so that's been the
number one hurdle.

00:42:29.580 --> 00:42:32.250
That one seems to have been
solved in the main malaria

00:42:32.250 --> 00:42:35.910
vector species and [INAUDIBLE].

00:42:35.910 --> 00:42:39.270
Other problems include to
make it evolutionarily stable,

00:42:39.270 --> 00:42:42.450
you have to program CRISPR
to cut many, many sites.

00:42:42.450 --> 00:42:44.970
That problem is still
being worked out.

00:42:44.970 --> 00:42:47.080
It's one that we're working on.

00:42:47.080 --> 00:42:49.380
Once you solve that and
put those two together,

00:42:49.380 --> 00:42:54.810
they have enough target
genes that it should work.

00:42:54.810 --> 00:42:55.870
What I don't know--

00:42:55.870 --> 00:43:01.810
so I think the social side of
'will every African country be

00:43:01.810 --> 00:43:02.850
able to agree?'

00:43:02.850 --> 00:43:04.434
is going to be the
limiting factor.

00:43:04.434 --> 00:43:06.850
There are people working on
that form of gene drive system

00:43:06.850 --> 00:43:08.380
and Aedes aegypti.

00:43:08.380 --> 00:43:10.360
I think it's a terrible idea.

00:43:10.360 --> 00:43:14.194
But, yeah, there's nothing I
can do about that beyond urge

00:43:14.194 --> 00:43:16.610
them to be a little bit more
open than what they currently

00:43:16.610 --> 00:43:17.480
are.

00:43:17.480 --> 00:43:20.720
And see if we can maybe get
the universities around here

00:43:20.720 --> 00:43:23.180
to agree to a patent pool
for ethical licensing

00:43:23.180 --> 00:43:25.389
to ensure that that work
and all other work is open.

